> where is the javascript/css for the slight blue glow when you select the comment textbox

  .comment-create textarea:focus {
    border-color: #000 !important;
  }

@ks: A little extension: Besides what you want to achieve, I guess that your post also presents a question: **Is it suitable to treat ‘\xa0’ as a common delimiter?**

From my first comment, there are people that want to directly convert it to space, so it's suitable to treat it as a delimiter. But some people like you want to keep it when splitting text. And it looks like that ‘\xa0’ has different use in different cases.

Also I have no answer :P

@Ulrichard: my fav is by using Kiwix, with it I can read lots of things offline. [Official resources](http://wiki.kiwix.org), many mirrors like [this one](https://mirrors.dotsrc.org/kiwix/zim/). I like reading Wikipedia, Wikivoyage, Wikisource.  [Android app](https://f-droid.org/packages/org.kiwix.kiwixmobile/), there is also [a headless app](https://aur.archlinux.org/packages/kiwix-cli-git/), so it can be used across different devices in the same network like ZeroNet. For books there is [Gutenburg](https://www.gutenberg.org/), and sorry for German fellows because it probably [gets blocked](https://goodereader.com/blog/e-book-news/project-gutenberg-blocks-german-users-from-downloading-ebooks). There are also old Gutenburg archives as Kiwix files (created in 2014), so I can have the whole library offline, English archive is 40G, a bit too large, German archive is fine (509M). And yep some books of mine are pirated, I'm proud of myself for downloading a lot of books shared by net friends when I was in university :3, even though my university already has many libraries and huge book collections, the book sharing environment online is very awful now.. and I just saw this news..: [Switzerland Takes Steps Against eBook Piracy](https://goodereader.com/blog/digital-publishing/switzerland-takes-steps-against-piracy).
--- ---
I agree that DRM is plague. With DRM, besides we can't share books, it's possible that all books will automatically get burned when Amazon goes down, I doubt if they have a solution now. If you really want some new published books to read, I think it's possible to contact the author to release it in DRM-free form, if the author can't because of some contract.. one solution is DRM-removed tool, or copy the content to another format. Ebook is a big business now, so unfornately things won't get better in these years I guess.

